{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640473"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:17:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:17:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17828"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17828"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0,0.97,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73287"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10542"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58758"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26002"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73287"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA key principle of medical ethics is respect for patient autonomy, which includes the right to make decisions about their own healthcare.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ethical and legal position regarding a patient\u0027s right to decline medical treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Patients can only decline non-essential treatments","Patients can only decline treatment with family agreement","Patients must accept treatment if recommended by two doctors","Patients with decision-making capacity can decline any treatment","Patients must accept life-saving treatments"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct position is that \u003Cstrong\u003Epatients with decision-making capacity can decline any treatment\u003C/strong\u003E, even if this decision may result in serious harm or death. This right is protected by law and ethical principles of autonomy and self-determination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent common misconceptions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatients can only decline non-essential treatments\u003C/strong\u003E - A patient has the right to refuse any treatment, regardless of whether it is considered essential or non-essential.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatients can only decline treatment with family agreement\u003C/strong\u003E - A capable patient\u0027s right to refuse treatment is independent of family views or wishes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatients must accept treatment if recommended by two doctors\u003C/strong\u003E - Medical recommendations, regardless of the number of doctors involved, do not override a capable patient\u0027s right to refuse.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatients must accept life-saving treatments\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no legal requirement for patients to accept any treatment, even those that could prevent death.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis right to decline treatment only applies when patients have decision-making capacity and have been appropriately informed of the risks and benefits of their choice. Exceptions exist for certain public health matters (like mandatory treatment of tuberculosis) or when patients lack capacity to make decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with decision-making capacity have the right to decline any medical treatment, even if this may result in harm.","Healthcare providers must respect a patient\u0027s autonomous choice to refuse treatment if they have been appropriately informed of the risks.","The only exceptions to respecting treatment refusal are when the patient lacks capacity or when their decision affects public health."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58758"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17828"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58758"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T10:26:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T10:26:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10542"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73287"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74